task-SLD_bold.json.TaskName: VisuoSpatial Working Memory, Large Reward, Delayed Feedback
task-SLD_bold.json.Instructions: Press the first finger if letters are in the same position and every time the cross turns red. Press the second finger if letters are NOT in the same position. Respond as fast as you can! Remember, the better you do the more money you can make!! You CAN respond as soon as each letter appears.
task-SLD_bold.json.TaskDescription: Subjects performed 48 trials of a 1-back visuospatial working memory (VSWM) task, 48 trials of a 2-back VSWM task, and 24 trials of a fixation task in a block design. Experimental task order was randomly generated with each experimental block followed by a 12 trial fixation block. Prior to the beginning of each experimental block, the program would indicate which task instructions were to be followed (1-back or 2-back). Throughout the experimental tasks, subjects were presented with an image indicating that they would make $.25 for each correct answer (/stimuli/fixation_ manycoins.bmp) in the middle of a black fixation square. In each trial, subjects were presented with a letter of the English alphabet in one of the four corners around the fixation square for 1200 ms followed by an 800 ms fixation period where only the fixation square remained. In the 1-back task, participants were instructed to press the first finger if the new letter was in the same position as the previously presented letter and to press the second finger if the position differed. In the 2-back task, participants were instructed to press the first finger if the new letter was in the same position as the letter presented two back and to press the second finger if the position differed. Participants could respond with a right handed button box during the duration of letter presentation (1200ms). At the end of each experimental block, participants were presented with their block accuracy. During fixation trials, subjects were presented with a black fixation cross for 600ms, 1200ms of either a black or red fixation cross, followed by 200ms of a black fixation cross. Subjects were instructed to press the first finger whenever a black fixation-cross turned red (4/12 trials).

duration.Description: Duration of trial from presentation of the letter to end of fixation period

During fixation trials, subjects were presented with a black fixation cross for 600ms, 1200ms of either a black or red fixation cross, followed by 200ms of a black fixation cross. Subjects were instructed to press the first finger whenever a black fixation-cross turned red (4/12 trials).

MeasurementToolMetadata.Citation: DuPaul, G. J., Power, T. J., Anastopoulos, A. D., & Reid, R. (1998). ADHD Rating Scale-IV: Checklists, norms, and clinical interpretation. New York: Guilford.

Q1.Description: Fails to give close attention to details or makes careless mistakes in schoolwork.

Q2.Description: Fidgets with hands or feet or squirms in seat.

Q3.Description: Has difficulty sustaining attention in tasks or play activities.

Q4.Description: Leaves seat in classroom or in other situations in which remaining seated is expected.

Q5.Description: Does not seem to listen when spoken to directly.

Q6.Description: Runs about or climbs excessively in situations in which it is inappropriate.

Q7.Description: Does not follow through on instructions and fails to finish work.

Q8.Description: Has difficulty playing or engaging in leisure activities quietly.

Q9.Description: Has difficulty organizing tasks and activities.

Q10.Description: Is on the go or acts as if driven by a motor.

Q11.Description: Avoids tasks (e.g. schoowork, homework) that require sustained mental effort.

Q13.Description: Loses things necessary for tasks or activities.

Q14.Description: Blurts out answers before questions have been completed.

Difficulty_Attention.Description: Difficulty Sustaining Attention on Tasks or Play Activities

levels.2: Subthreshold: Occasionallly has difficulty sustaining attention on tasks or play activites. Problem has minimal effect on functioning.
levels.3: Threshold: Often has difficulty sustaining attention. Problem has moderate to severe effect on functioning

levels.2: Subthreshold: Occasionallly forgetful. Problem has only minimal effect on functioning.
levels.3: Threshold: Attention often disrupted by minor distractions other kids would be able to ignore. Problem has moderate to severe effect on functioning.

levels.3: Threshold: Often has difficulty remaining seated when required to do so. Problem has moderate to severe effect on functioning.

levels.3: Threshold: Often makes careless mistakes. Problem has moderate to severe effect on functioning.

levels.3: Threshold: Often does not listen. Problem has moderate to severe effect on functioning.

levels.3: Threshold: Often has difficulty following instructions. Problem has moderate to severe effect on functioning.

levels.3: Threshold: Often disorganized. Problem has moderate to severe effect on functioning.

levels.2: Subthreshold: Occasionallly loses things. Problem has only minimal effect on functioning.

levels.2: Subthreshold: Occasionallly forgetful. Problem has only minimal effect on functioning.

levels.3: Threshold: Often interrupts others.

README:
#Experimental Design

This experiment was implemented in E-prime following the design described in the
task-<task>_bold.json files as well as illustrated in stimuli/task_design.jpg

#Sessions

At ses-T1 subjects competed standardized testing (located in phenotype/) as
well as imaging sessions. At ses-T2 subjects only completed standardized
testing.

#Defacing

Anatomical images were defaced according to procedure described in Lytle, McNorgan, & Booth (2019) (https://doi.org/10.1038/s41597-019-0338-5)
